---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="About"
  description="Disabled by Design — what the name means, who June is, and the design orientation behind the work."
>
  <div class="page-header">
    <h1><span class="rose">Disabled</span> by <span class="rose">Design</span></h1>
  </div>

  <div class="about-content">
    <p>
      I design from the standpoint of a disabled person — disability is a parameter through
      which I engage with the world, and it lets me perceive things somebody with a different
      neurotype would not have thought of. That's a feature, not a deficit.
    </p>
    <p>
      The name also names the problem: systems are <em>designed</em> in ways that produce
      disability. Rigid deadlines, surveillance grading, deficit-model assessments — the
      infrastructure disables people, then calls the people broken. The social model of
      disability applied to every structure I study and build.
    </p>
    <p>
      And there's the third meaning. Against the impulse to genetic-engineer away disability,
      against the calculation that some bodies are acceptable casualties. I don't want a future
      that optimizes me out. My existence is a fucking asset. I'm right here.
    </p>
  </div>

  <section>
    <h2>The Design Orientation</h2>
    <div class="about-content">
      <p>
        I don't just build software that accomplishes a task. I reinvent the ways we do things
        by interrogating the constitutive power relations and forms of structural violence —
        and design systems for <em>that</em>. The classroom becomes a strike. The assignment
        becomes a launchpad for discussion, not an endpoint for evaluation. The AI response
        becomes mandatory critical analysis through 76 frameworks.
      </p>
      <p>
        Each of these follows the same pattern: identify the structural violence embedded in
        the existing approach, critique it, build something that operates from different
        assumptions. The critique and the code are the same practice.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Survival Architecture</h2>
    <div class="about-content">
      <p>
        Every tool I've built emerged from conditions that demanded it. Teaching four classes
        of 42&ndash;49 students without a TA at a Hispanic-Serving Institution under a new state
        mandate. Losing the ability to focus on reading under political crisis. Watching a
        classroom become a site where fascism normalizes itself. A well-funded lab would not
        have built capacity-responsive pacing or tangent capture because they wouldn't have
        needed them. The survival architecture concept is literal.
      </p>
      <p>
        "The conditions that make me precarious are the same conditions that made this system
        necessary and possible."
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
